observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct:
a) The inventory Committee to complete the physical count of Property, Plant and Equipment and ensure that the specific descriptions of the PPE are properly indicated in the RPCPPE;
b) The Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the General Services Office, to investigate the noted discrepancies, reconcile the amounts recorded in the books with the RPCPPE, and effect the necessary adjustments;
c) The GSO, in coordination with the Municipal Accountant, to exert effort in locating the documents needed in providing the details of each PPE account and to provide the Item Number of each PPE in the RPCPPE;
d) The GSO and Accounting Office to regularly update the Property Cards (PC) and PPE Ledger Cards for all PPE accounts; and
e) The Municipal Accountant to reclassify the erroneous entries made from the CIP-Infrastructure Assets and Building account, and transfer the tangible items below the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00 to the appropriate semi-expendable asset account.
We also recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to implement the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts as provided under COA Circular No. 2020-006 to finally establish the PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:

a. Direct the Inventory Committee to committee to complete the physical inventory of all its property and prepare the RPCPPE in accordance with the prescribed format;

b. Require the Property Officer to update the property records based on the results of physical inventory and reconcile with the accounting records;

c. Instruct the Property Officer and Municipal Accountant to ensure that all PPEs Included in the Property Unit and the PPELCs maintained by the Accounting Unit;

d. Direct the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary journal entries to adjust the Road Network account; and 

e. Avail the one-time cleaning of PPE account balances, provided the guidelines and procedures embodied in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 are strictly followed.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:

Require from the concerned AOs the immediate liquidation of their outstanding cash advance and refund the unutilized balances;

Direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to ensure that the amount of cash advance is equal to the net amount of the payroll for a pay period;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to see to it that the liquidation documents are in accordance to the purpose which the cash advance is granted;

Cease the granting additional cash advances to AOs with unliquidated cash advances;


Direct the Municipal Accountant to send out demand letters periodically to concerned officials indicating the period or deadlines within which the concerned official may liquidate the cash advances, otherwise, withholding of the payment of their salaries shall be made in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular no. 97-002;

Refrain from grating cash advances to elected officials two months prior to end/term of office and require payment of unliquidated cash advances otherwise the same shall be deducted from their salaries or clearance shall not be issued thereof; and 

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to notify the concerned accountable officers that failure to liquidate their cash advance within the prescribe period are subject to imposition of administrative liability and corresponding penalties as embodied per CSC MC No. 23, series of 2019.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
Direct the Inventory Committee to complete the physical inventory of all its property and prepare the RPCPPE in accordance with the prescribed format;
Require the Property Officer to update the property records based on the results of actual physical inventory and reconcile with the Accounting records;
Instruct the Property Officer and Municipal Accountant to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the Property Unit and the PPELCs maintained by the Accounting Unit;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with concerned departments for the proper recording of projects;
Require the Municipal Accountant to verify the CIP accounts;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary journal entries to adjust the PPE accounts; and
Avail the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, provided the guidelines and procedures embodied in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 are strictly followed.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Conduct proper analysis of transactions pertaining to the Due to NGAs and Due to LGUs account and make proper adjustments for deficiencies;
Maintain subsidiary ledgers for each fund received from NGAs and monitor closely the transactions pertaining thereto;
Exert effort in retrieving data and information and coordinate with source agencies concerned to eliminate the prior years’ balances; and
Refund to the source agencies fund transfers that could no longer be implemented.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
Direct the Municipal Agriculturist to furnish the distribution lists of  inventories released under the Municipal Agriculture Office to the Head of GSO;
Direct the Head of the GSO to prepare and submit the SSMI together with the RIS of all issued inventories to the Municipal Accountant;
Require the Municipal Accountant to record in the books all issued  inventories;
Require the Municipal Accountant to make necessary adjustment for the erroneous recording of the Advances to Contractor account as inventories; and
Henceforth, require the periodic reconciliation by the Municipal Accountant and  Head of GSO of their records relative to the procurement and issuances of supplies and materials to avoid misstatements of inventory accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed:

a. Direct the Inventory Committee to complete the physical count of all its inventories and prepare the RPCI in accordance with the prescribed format;

b.  Require the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to reconcile their records based on the results of the physical inventory;

c.  Henceforth, require the Inventory Committee to conduct semestrally the physical count of inventories and prepare the RCPI; and 

d. Submit to the  Auditor the RPCI not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the;

Municipal Accountant to see to it that all disbursement vouchers are duly supported with complete documentation to ensure the propriety, validity and legality of the claims and to avoid suspension of disbursements in audit; and

Officials concerned to submit the necessary supporting documents to the Audit Team to determine the validity of the transactions.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:

a. Municipal Account to maintain separate RAAOs for the current appropriations of the LDRRMF. The balance of the appropriation of LDRRMF Fund at the end of the year will be transferred to the Special Trust Fund;

b. Municipal Accountant to set up separate ledgers in the special trust fund for the transferred unutilized balance of DRRMF in the General Fund by year;

c.   MDRRMO to submit to the Audit Team a monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of LDRRMF duly prepared and certified by the Municipal Accountant reflecting the available funds, utilization and balances of the yearly special trust fund; and

d. Municipal Accountant to reconcile the balances of the LDRRM Fund in the registries and the balances reflected in the books.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer to adhere with the guidelines on the grant and utilization of cash advances per COA Circular No. 97-002;

Instruct the General Services Officer/BAC Chairman to comply with the rules and regulations on the procurement of goods and services for COVID-19 related PPAs pursuant to DBM LBC No. 124 and GPPB Circular No. 01-2020;

Require the Municipal Treasurer to issue checks directly to the payees or in the name of establishments per Section 93 of PD No. 1445; and

Compel the Special Disbursing Officers to liquidate the cash advance in the amount of ₱300,000.00. 

We further recommended that the Municipal Accountant submit the necessary supporting documents noted in audit.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive: 

Instruct the MDRRMO to submit the required supporting documents to be attached to the Summary/List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances such as the acknowledgement receipts for in-kind donations, official receipts for cash donations and inventory list of the undistributed items or goods;

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to issue Official Receipts on all cash donations received and maintain a separate bank account with an authorized government depository bank;

Delegate to the General Services Officer the receiving of in-kind donations and the inventory and monitoring thereof; and

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the concerned Disbursing Officer, Special Disbursing Officers and retired elected officials and employees to liquidate their long outstanding cash advances;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to send out demand letters periodically to concerned officials indicating the period or deadline within which the concerned officials may liquidate the cash advances, otherwise, withholding of the payment of their salaries shall be made in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002;
Stop granting additional cash advances with the same purpose/s to the concerned Disbursing Officer, Special Disbursing Officers, employees and elected officials unless their previous cash advances are settled and proper accounting thereof are made;
Refrain from granting cash advances to elected employees two months prior to end/term of office and require payment of unliquidated cash advances, otherwise, the same shall be deducted from their salaries or clearance shall not be issued thereof; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to notify the concerned accountable officers  that failure to liquidate their cash advances within the prescribe period are subject to imposition of administrative liability and corresponding penalties as embodied per CSC MC No. 23, series of 2019.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Require the concerned Disbursing Officer, Special Disbursing Officers and retired elected officials and employees to liquidate their long outstanding cash advances. Demand letters should be sent periodically to concerned officials to immediately liquidate their cash advances, otherwise, withholding of the payment of salaries of accountable officers shall be made in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002;

Stop granting additional cash advances with the same purpose/s to the concerned Disbursing Officer, Special Disbursing Officers, employees and elected officials unless their previous cash advances are settled and proper accounting thereof are made;

Refrain from granting cash advances to elected employees two months prior to end/term of office and require payment of unliquidated cash advances, otherwise, the same shall be deducted from their salaries or clearance shall not be issued thereof; and

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to notify the concerned accountable officers that failure to liquidate their cash advances within the prescribe period are subject to imposition of administrative liability and corresponding penalties as embodied per CSC MC No. 23, series of 2019.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Issue addendum to the MOA regarding the provision of schedule and terms of payment and corresponding surcharges for delayed payment by the Lambunao Water District;




Direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to send monthly billing to the LWD and improve the collection strategies of the municipality by monitoring the payments made;

Require the officials concerned to oversee the compliance of the second party to the provisions of the MOA executed by and between the Municipality of Lambunao and Lambunao Water District.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:

The MEEDO Head to revisit the ordinances relative to revenue generations particularly on the operation of the Municipal Economic Enterprise to ensure that the provisions of the revenue code were efficiently and effectively implemented;


The MEEDO Head to submit monthly reports on the status of receipts and collections including statement of delinquencies of the economic enterprises;

The Municipal Treasurer to formulate strategic measures to intensify collection efficiency especially in RGU Lambunao Water System.

The Local Finance Committee, the MEEDO Head and the Sangguniang Bayan to conduct an assessment of all existing RGUs in order to determine and resolve the incurrence of loss.

We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor consider going over the manual on procedures, if financial self-sufficiency is not achieved, i.e. item 7.3(e) of LBC No. 111.

